  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 12:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"He will not suffer (יתּן) the destroyer to come into your houses:\" Jehovah effected the destruction of the first-born through המּשׁחית, the destroyer, or destroying angel, ὁ ὁλοθρεύων (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 11:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., not a fallen angel, but the angel of Jehovah, in whom Jehovah revealed Himself to the patriarchs and Moses. This is not at variance with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 78:49",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; for the writer of this psalm regards not only the slaying of the first-born, but also the pestilence (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 9:1-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as effected through the medium of angels of evil: though, according to the analogy of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 13:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", המּשׁחית might certainly be understood collectively as applying to a company of angels. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 12:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"This word,\" i.e., the instructions respecting the Passover, they were to regard as an institution for themselves and their children for ever (עד־עולם in the same sense as עולם, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 17:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 17:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and when dwelling in the promised land, they were to explain the meaning of this service to their sons. The ceremony is called עבדה, \"service,\" inasmuch as it was the fulfilment of a divine command, a performance demanded by God, though it promoted the good of Israel.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
